{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491591"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:54:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"993"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/993"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.06,0.11,0.66,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30650"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/993"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"993"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"604"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42191"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30650"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents with high fever, a morbilliform eruption on his arms and trunk (Image), together with facial swelling. He is normally well other than a recent diagnosis of epilepsy which was started on sodium valproate six weeks ago. His blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb 130 (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC 16 (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 150 (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils 3 (0-0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils 4 (2-8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP 170 (30-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 85 (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 110 (5-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT 65 (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 380 (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 15 (3-8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EViral serologies are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the likely cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis","Eczema herpeticum","Erythroderma","DRESS syndrome","Toxic epidermal necrolysis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDRESS syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (Severe drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms) is a type 4 hypersensitivity. The onset of symptoms usually develop 2 \u2013 8 weeks after the commencing the culprit medication - usually anti-convulsants. Patients present with high grade fever, morbilliform eruption, facial swelling and mucosal involvement in some cases. Blood tests may reveal leucocytosis, eosinophilia and evidence of multi-organ involvement. Most common involvement is liver with deranged liver function test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute generalised exanthematous pustulosis is an acute onset pustular, diffuse rash secondary to a drug reaction - commonly beta-lactam antibiotics. It occurs within 5 days of administration in most cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEczema herpeticum is when skin affected or previously affected by atopic dermatitis (eczema) becomes infected with herpes simplex virus. It is a painful, itchy pustular rash which can be localised or generalised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythroderma is a general term used to describe a wide spread, erythematous rash covering \u0026gt;90% of body surface area. It could fit with the initial description of the rash but does not explain all features (e.g. facial swelling) nor the blood results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EToxic epidermal necrolysis is a good differential as it is characterised by fever, and then a widespread (\u0026gt;30% TBSA) erythematous rash with mucosal involvement. As it progresses, it leads to blistering of the skin and is associated with a high mortality rate; not present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The DRESS syndrome may not appear until two months after the start of the culprit medication."],"references":["Choudhary S, McLoed M, Torchia D, Romanello P. Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) Syndrome. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol. 2013; 6(6): 31-37.","Ngan V. Erythroderma. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2003 [updated 2016; cited 2021 Feb 10]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/erythroderma/.","Lin CY. Eczema herpeticum. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2010 [cited 2021 Feb 10]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/eczema-herpeticum/.","Purvis D. Acute generalised exanthematous pustulosis. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2008 [cited 2021 Feb 10]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/acute-generalised-exanthematous-pustulosis/.","Toxic epidermal necrolysis. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2008 [cited 2021 Feb 10]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/cme/emergencies/toxic-epidermal-necrolysis/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16593"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"993"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18477"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18477","links